---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
import { Image } from 'astro:assets'

import img_urban from '~/assets/urban_areas.png'
import img_green from '~/assets/green_areas.png'
import img_centres from '~/assets/centralities.png'
import img_unbuildable from '~/assets/unbuildable_areas.png'

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL
const dg = (name: string) => `${base}images/${name}.svg`
---

<BaseLayout>
  <h1>Isobenefit Urbanism — QGIS Plugin</h1>
  <h6>Brainstorming walkable, nature-rich urban growth on real-world data</h6>

  <section>
    <p>
      The <strong>Isobenefit Urbanism</strong> plugin for QGIS simulates how a place could grow so that
      everyone keeps walkable access to <strong>both</strong> local centres (shops, services) <strong>and</strong>
      green space — then distils that simulation into a concrete <strong>recommended plan</strong> you can
      discuss with planners. It runs on your own GIS layers. It is an exploratory, conversational tool used
      alongside local knowledge, not a prescription.
    </p>
    <nav class="toc">
      <a href="#concept">Concept</a>
      <a href="#install">Install</a>
      <a href="#inputs">Inputs</a>
      <a href="#simulation">The simulation</a>
      <a href="#plan">From runs to a plan</a>
      <a href="#postprocessing">Post-processing</a>
      <a href="#outputs">Outputs</a>
      <a href="#demonstration">Demonstration</a>
      <a href="#parameters">Parameters</a>
      <a href="#credits">Credits</a>
    </nav>
  </section>

  <h2 id="concept">Concept &amp; rationale</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      <a href="https://lucadacci.wixsite.com/dacci/isobenefit-urbanism-morphogenesis">Isobenefit Urbanism</a>
      (Luca D'Acci) describes a city whose benefits — nearness to centres and to nature — are spread
      <em>evenly</em>: quality of life shouldn't depend on which corner of town you live in. It steers between
      the two failure modes of growth: <strong>sprawl</strong>, which strands people far from centres and
      paves over nature, and <strong>overcrowding</strong>, which squeezes nature out.
    </p>
    <p>
      The plugin turns that principle into a <strong>cellular-automaton</strong> simulation: a grid of land
      cells grows step by step under rules that keep new development on foot of a centre and protect green
      corridors. Because the rules are stochastic, no single run is "the" answer — so the plugin runs many and
      reports both the <strong>uncertainty</strong> (where development is robust vs contingent) and one
      coherent <strong>recommended plan</strong>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="install">Install the plugin</h2>
  <section>
    <ol>
      <li>
        In QGIS (3.x or 4.x): <em>Plugins → Manage and Install Plugins → Settings →</em> tick
        <em>"Show also experimental plugins"</em>, then search for <strong>isobenefit</strong> and install it.
      </li>
      <li>
        On first run it checks for the <code>isobenefit</code> simulation engine and, if missing, offers to
        install it into the QGIS Python environment (needs internet). <strong>Restart QGIS</strong> afterwards.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      If automatic install is blocked, run it yourself with the QGIS Python:
    </p>
    <pre><code>&lt;qgis-python&gt; -m pip install "isobenefit&gt;=0.9,&lt;0.10"</code></pre>
    <p>
      <strong>Why two pieces?</strong> The plugin itself is thin (UI + GIS I/O). The heavy compute is a
      separate Rust engine published to PyPI as the <code>isobenefit</code> package — kept apart because the
      QGIS plugin repository doesn't permit shipping compiled binaries. Source for both:
      <a href="https://github.com/UCL/BSP-isobenefit-qgis-plugin">BSP-isobenefit-qgis-plugin</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="inputs">Inputs</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      Only a polygon <strong>extents</strong> layer and a projected <strong>CRS</strong> are required. Everything
      else is optional context that constrains the simulation:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>existing built areas, green space (preserved), and unbuildable land (rivers, steep ground)</li>
      <li>urban centres — as polygon areas or point seeds</li>
      <li>public-transport stops, rail / tram stations, and a street network</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="img-row">
      <figure><Image src={img_urban} alt="" quality="max" width="380" /><figcaption>Existing built areas</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><Image src={img_green} alt="" quality="max" width="380" /><figcaption>Existing green areas</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><Image src={img_centres} alt="" quality="max" width="380" /><figcaption>Urban centres</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><Image src={img_unbuildable} alt="" quality="max" width="380" /><figcaption>Unbuildable land</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <p>
      No layers prepared? The companion <strong>Extract from OpenStreetMap</strong> tool downloads built, green,
      centre, street and public-transport layers for an area of interest and drops them straight into the
      project, ready to edit and run.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="simulation">The simulation</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      Each step, the cellular automaton visits the land grid and decides whether an undeveloped cell may be
      built. The rules, in order:
    </p>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_0')} alt="Step 0: population target" /><figcaption>Stop once the target population is reached; otherwise keep growing.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_1c')} alt="Step 1: periphery" /><figcaption>Only empty cells on the <em>periphery</em> of existing built land are candidates (already-built and far-flung cells are skipped).</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_2')} alt="Step 2: centre walk" /><figcaption>The candidate must be within a <em>centre walk</em> of a centrality — so new homes stay near a centre.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_3')} alt="Step 3: green span" /><figcaption>Building must not shrink a green corridor below the <em>minimum green span</em> — protecting access to nature.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_4')} alt="Step 4: build" /><figcaption>If every check passes the cell is built; its density is set by distance to the nearest centre (denser closer in).</figcaption></figure>
    <h3>Where new centres come from</h3>
    <p>
      As development spreads beyond a walk of any centre, the simulation can seed a new one. How readily it does
      so — and whether settlements leapfrog away from the core — is the <strong>Dispersed development</strong>
      dial (Off / Moderate / Aggressive).
    </p>
    <div class="diagram-pair">
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('centres_neighbouring')} alt="" /><figcaption>A <em>neighbouring</em> centre seeds where built land outgrows a walk of any centre.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('centres_isolated')} alt="" /><figcaption>An <em>isolated</em> centre lets a satellite settlement leapfrog away from the core.</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <p>
      Two further dials shape growth: <strong>build probability</strong> (the per-step growth rate — lower is
      tighter and more compact, higher is faster and looser) and the <strong>density range</strong> (min–max),
      which the engine spreads as a gradient that densifies toward centres.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="plan">From many runs to one plan</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      A single run is just one plausible future; a different random seed gives a different — but equally valid —
      layout. So the plugin runs an <strong>ensemble</strong> and does two distinct things with it.
    </p>
    <div class="diagram-pair">
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_ensemble')} alt="" /><figcaption>Average the runs into <em>likelihood</em> layers: an uncertainty map of where development is robust vs contingent.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_select')} alt="" /><figcaption>A probability surface isn't a buildable plan — so also pick the single best run (shortest average walk to amenities).</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <h2 id="postprocessing">Post-processing the chosen run</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      The chosen run is tidied into the recommended plan. Post-processing deliberately changes <strong>only the
      centres</strong> (plus a gentle building cleanup) — the buildings come from the simulation.
    </p>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_cleanup')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Cleanup:</strong> tiny stranded settlements below the minimum size revert to green. It's gentle, and the raw plan is saved too, so the change stays visible.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_centring')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Centre placement:</strong> each centre is moved to the <em>interior</em> of its contiguous built area — on built land and central to it, never on an edge or in a gap.</figcaption></figure>
    <p>
      Finally, centres are offered at two <strong>clustering</strong> strengths — the same buildings, but fewer
      and larger centres as you cluster harder (coverage trades off). You compare the options and pick; see the
      <a href="#demonstrators">demonstrators</a> below.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="outputs">Outputs</h2>
  <section>
    <p>An ensemble run writes a small, self-explaining set of layers:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>existing development</strong> — the baseline, before the simulation</li>
      <li><strong>raw (before post-processing)</strong> — the chosen run as grown, kept for comparison</li>
      <li><strong>moderately / tightly clustered centres</strong> — the two recommended-plan options to choose between</li>
      <li><strong>development likelihood</strong> (built, green) — the ensemble uncertainty map</li>
      <li><strong><code>_report.txt</code></strong> — a record of the parameters and per-option statistics</li>
    </ul>
    <figure>
      <img class="demo" src={dg('demo_recommended_plan')} alt="A recommended plan" />
      <figcaption>A recommended plan from a real run: an existing core (brown) keeps its centre, new growth (grey) clusters into settlements, each centred, within a green matrix.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <h2 id="demonstration">Visual demonstration</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      Each figure below is a <strong>real pipeline run</strong>, rendered in the plan's own visual language at
      high resolution — so they show what each control actually does, not a hand-drawn impression.
    </p>

    <h3>Dispersed development</h3>
    <p>
      From one compact town to scattered satellites. Even <em>Moderate</em> keeps a dominant core; only
      <em>Aggressive</em> loses any single centre of gravity.
    </p>
    <div class="demo-row">
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_dispersal_off')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Off</strong> — one compact, contiguous town</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_dispersal_moderate')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Moderate</strong> — a dominant town with satellites</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_dispersal_aggressive')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Aggressive</strong> — many satellites, no single core</figcaption></figure>
    </div>

    <h3>Build probability</h3>
    <p>The per-step growth rate: over the same number of steps, faster growth reaches much further.</p>
    <div class="demo-row">
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_buildprob_slow')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Slow (0.08)</strong> — a small, tight town</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_buildprob_fast')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Fast (0.6)</strong> — far more grown in the same time</figcaption></figure>
    </div>

    <h3>Centre clustering</h3>
    <p>The same buildings, two centre arrangements — clustering harder gives fewer, larger, more central centres.</p>
    <div class="demo-row">
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_clustering_moderate')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Moderately clustered</strong> — more, smaller centres</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_clustering_tight')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Tightly clustered</strong> — fewer, larger centres</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <h2 id="parameters">Parameters</h2>
  <section>
    <p>The run dialog groups the controls:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Simulation</strong> — max iterations, grid size, target population, build probability, Dispersed development, random seed</li>
      <li><strong>Walkable access</strong> — centre walk and green walk (each its own threshold)</li>
      <li><strong>Post-processing</strong> — optimise centre placement, minimum settlement area, minimum green span</li>
      <li><strong>Density</strong> — min, max, and existing-built density</li>
      <li><strong>Output &amp; input layers</strong> — the output path, CRS, and the layers above</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <h2 id="credits">Credits &amp; sources</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      Based on the <a href="https://lucadacci.wixsite.com/dacci/isobenefit-urbanism-morphogenesis">Isobenefit
      Urbanism</a> concept by Luca D'Acci, with original
      <a href="https://github.com/mitochevole/isobenefit-cities">Python code</a> by Michele Voto. Developed as
      part of the Future Urban Growth project at <strong>UCL Bartlett School of Planning</strong> (Tommaso
      Gabrieli, Luca D'Acci, Heeseo Kwon, Stephen Marshall, Valentina Marin Maureira, Gareth Simons). Code:
      <a href="https://github.com/UCL/BSP-isobenefit-qgis-plugin">BSP-isobenefit-qgis-plugin</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <footer>© 2026 UCL Bartlett School of Planning</footer>

  <style>
    .toc {
      @apply my-3 flex flex-wrap gap-x-4 gap-y-1 text-sm font-medium;
    }
    .toc a {
      @apply no-underline;
    }
    section {
      @apply border-t-1 border-theme pb-2;
    }
    ol {
      @apply ml-4 list-decimal;
    }
    ol li {
      @apply my-2 text-sm font-light;
    }
    .diagram {
      @apply w-full max-w-4xl;
    }
    .demo {
      @apply w-full max-w-md;
    }
    .img-row,
    .demo-row,
    .diagram-pair {
      @apply flex flex-wrap items-start justify-center gap-4;
    }
    footer {
      @apply mt-8 flex justify-center border-t-1 border-theme p-2 text-xs font-light italic;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
